Nothing particularly impressive compared to world trade in real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) showed interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "in competition with the dollar or euro" and "like the conventional currencies".
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies such as the "Credits" that are used to move forward in a video game that can be won or purchased by games (and sometimes also exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is controlled and processed by a central authority every time.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are collectors of the accounts, auditors, money issuers and buyers and sellers at the same time.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A series of data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way the network can check the authenticity of the transaction.
With the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the handled bitcoins are available in the account book of public accounts distributed throughout the network.
The decisive step is to include this new transaction in this book.
This happens via a mathematical task launched on the computers, whereas the winner, which is a kind of temporary central banker, has the privilege of adding this additional line.
It is a fragment of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and clearer electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before the whole "hacked".
The aim is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right one.
The transaction is therefore permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If one user wants to pay the same money for deceit twice very fast (less than 10 minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other remains without link, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task receives 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The Bitcoins in circulation are therefore limited to 21 million but can be divided up to a hundred million set, which leaves a certain play room...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with any improvement in the performance of calculation.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin were attacked and stolen the Bitcoin deposits.
"The weakness used does not concern the actual protocol," assures Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a company for payment with real money and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also reveals these deficiencies.
Important actors such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others like the blog platform WordPress.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Wiizmann Institute in Israel analysed the accounts and showed that almost 80% of Bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November a "mega-closure sale" was started.
"Three thousand dollars were exchanged," Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, who converted Bitcoins to gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book on this currency, believes firmly in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
His system Paytunia corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions that are cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented in dealers, and latter do not have to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just need to specify an address that can be photographed and detected by a telephone, Pierre Noizat assures that he has thousands of users.
It is a general trend to cover hierarchical systems in favour of more horizontally oriented systems.
"It will take some time until Bitcoin continues, but 2013 could be a turnpoint," he predicts.
In its report, the ECB also provides for the re-evaluation of the various risks considered today in the event of the success of this currency.
