At its beginning in 1956, the Polish space society PTA tried to join the International Space Federation established in 1951, and the PTA became a ordinary member in the autumn of 1956.
In the following year the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Vice-President of the International Federation for Space.
He had this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA took a major part in the development of the extremely successful meteorological missile (Raketa Meteorologiczna), the first Polish missile for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first started on October 10, 1958.
The missile with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh a total of 5 kg.
Later an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959, flight tests started with the two-level RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
A further development level should already be able to do real scientific work - the rocket RM-34 should reach a flight height of up to 14.5 km and be used for monitoring high winds.
However, in 1962 the further development was stopped.
Follower of the first type RM rocket was the meteor-1 rocket developed in the years 1962 to 1965.
The missile was designed as a two-level missile, its total length was 510 cm and the initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed from this missile, which differ in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The meteor-1A missile has a transport room of 0.4 litres of capacity, meteor-1B of 0.34 litres and meteor-1C of 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight height was 37 km for all three types.
In the years 1965 to 1968, the meteor 2 missile was developed in the aviation institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a start weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a 10 kg use load to a height of approximately 60 km.
Afterwards, the versions of Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which followed the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites in the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after the Czech Republic of Vladimír Remek.
