Finalisation of the Unasur Summit without publishing the Declaration of Lima
The sixth summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without publication of the Declaration of Lima, which was announced in advance and should be theoretically signed by the seven present governments.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the VI. ordinary meeting of the Heads of State and Government of the Unasur. Sources in the State and Presidential Office initially informed them that they would be transferred after the Clausur, however, explained that it would be published at a certain time on the website of the Peruan Government.
In the case of questions concerning the text, they stated that the content was presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief explanations to the press.
The access of journalists to information on the summit was limited at any time.
During the day, only the picture of the presidential meeting was transferred in the press room with the message "private session, limited audio".
The few information circulated among the journalists was received by the press speakers of some of the governments present at the meeting of Unasur, but not by the Peruan press speakers.
The only document that was distributed during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused discomfort in the hundreds of journalists of various national and international media, which demanded more information.
Following that, the President-in-Office of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the "Complete Statement" of the summit, but it was the Declaration of Humala and not the official document on the conclusion of the summit.
Last October, Peru was host of the IIIrd Summit of South America - Arab States (ASPA), and even on this occasion, despite the press’s strong call, the so - called Declaration of Lima, which had been announced in advance, was not published.
On the official website of the ASPA, you can be convinced that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruan authorities stressed that the information systems were available for journalists, but in a great extent limited access to information.
The summit also ended with the common commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment by the Hague Court of Justice, which arises from a border conflict between both countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would adopt the decision of the IGH, which starts on Monday in Den Haag, in the process that introduced the Lima against Santiago to listen to the pledoyers on both sides.
"We will follow and execute the judgment on the differences we are presenting to this International Court," said Humala together with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, was and continues to be a country that adheres to international laws, seeks peaceful solutions for disputes, concludes agreements and undergoes international courts," adds Piñera and greeted Humala with a handprint before the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of both Presidents that they would be subject to the IGH took place after Colombia, following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which considered it a serious mistake, had appealed against the Bogotá Agreement, which agreed to submit to the judgments of the International Court of Justice.
At the summit, the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner were present.
Paraguay, who has been excluded from Unasur since 2011 after his president Fernando Lugo's release, has not participated in the meeting.
The hosting president Ollanta Humala opened the conversations in the morning and ended the summit in Lima shortly after lunch.
The Head of State left the final document in which it announced that 16 decisions were taken and that the action lines for 31 projects between the South American countries were set over an investment amount of a total of $17 billion.
On the decisions taken, he said that the countries of Unasur "will take significant steps towards the objective of a South American citizenship, to which we will extend the decisions on residence rights."
He informed that measures would be promoted to improve cooperation in the fight against urban uncertainty and organised transnational crimes, as well as measures to improve access to drugs and to the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act in common and efficiently in the case of natural disasters.
With the crisis in Europe, "the economic consolidation (in Latin America) is not allowed to take triumphant trains, but is intended to expand our production performance and show our people a better future", Humala added.
"We have decided to give a number of 31 symbolic projects the priority to improve the geographical relations in South America and especially in rural and border areas... and thus unite our countries and create new economic forms," said the Peruan President in a read-out statement.
Among these projects are five Peruans, which are located on the crossings of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which are supposed to provide a better connection with Ecuador, although he did not give further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the election process in this country will serve for its resumption in the Union of South American nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbourhood relations was another aspect highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before his participating in the regional meeting that he expected a meeting with his counterpart of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, to treat the maritime conflict with respect after a judgment of the IGH questioned by Bogotá.
"I may meet with President Daniel Ortega on the morning ( Saturday)," said Santos.
